 1374","about 1353":"about 1353","1405":"1405","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Newbury, Berkshire, England","Earth, By Saltash, Corn, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Earth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Middle English  <i>erthe</i> in the sense ‘plot of arable land’ (Old English  <i>erþ</i>)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":37,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Geoffrey de Earth was born in 1345, in Newbury, Berkshire, England, his father, Sir Henry de Earth, was 47 and his mother, Lady Helena Beckstead, was 45. He married Lady Elizabeth about 1374, in Newbury, Berkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in 1405, in Ely, Cambridgeshire, England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1345–1405":"1345–1405","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1299–1353":"1299–1353","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1437":"1437","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1299":"1299","1375":"1375","1353":"1353","1382":"1382","about 1374":"umbes 1374","about 1353":"umbes 1353","1405":"1405","Ely, Cambridgeshire, England":"Ely, Cambridgeshire, England","Newbury, Berkshire, England":"Newbury, Berkshire, England","Earth, By Saltash, Corn, England":"Saltash, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England"},"fi":{"1345–1405":"1345–1405","1355–1437":"1355–1437","1375–1437":"1375–1437","1299–1353":"1299–1353","1300–Female":"1300–Kuollut","1437":"1437","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1355":"1355","1299":"1299","1375":"1375","1353":"